---
folder: runbooks
id-format: "NNNN-kebab-slug.md"
---
## Purpose
Repeatable operational procedures — the copy-pasteable steps for a recurring task or
recovery. "When X, do these steps." NOT the narrative of a one-off outage (→ incidents/,
which links here) and NOT design rationale (→ architectures/). A good runbook is
verifiable: each step has an expected result.

## File template
Frontmatter: `id`, `title`, `status`, `created`, `updated`, `links`.
Body:
- `## When to use` — the trigger condition / symptom that sends you here.
- `## Prerequisites` — access, tools, KUBECONFIG, out-of-band paths (KVM, etc.).
- `## Steps` — numbered, each with the exact command and the expected result.
- `## Verification` — how to confirm success.
- `## Notes / gotchas` — traps specific to this cluster.

## Retro rules
Extract any procedure performed more than once, or worth doing the same way next time:
recovery flows, deploy-via-GitOps, forced Flux reconcile, node/IP fixes, containerd
cleanup. When a procedure is refined (a better command, an extra safety step), update the
runbook in place. Prefer this cluster's real values (IPs, hostnames, KUBECONFIG path) over
generic placeholders.

## Cross-linking
Referenced by `[[incidents/NNNN]]` (the outage this recovers from) and
`[[architectures/NNNN]]` (the decision this operationalizes); links to affected
`[[services/NNNN]]`.
